{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568789","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568789"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:22:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:22:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21383"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"21383","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/21383"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.02,0.91,0.02,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14256"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101127"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"14256","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/14256"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21383"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83561"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"147"},{"type":"tags","id":"2166"},{"type":"tags","id":"3514"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"5753"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"12799"},{"type":"tags","id":"12804"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"34796"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40199"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43748"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101127","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101127"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a three-hour history of worsening shortness of breath, chest tightness, and wheezing. She is 28 weeks pregnant with her first child. She has a medical history of asthma since childhood and was recently diagnosed with gestational diabetes at 24 weeks. Her medications include salbutamol inhaler as needed and metformin 500 mg twice daily. She reports good adherence to her gestational diabetes diet plan.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears distressed with a pulse rate of 110/min, blood pressure 130/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. Chest examination reveals widespread expiratory wheeze. Abdominal examination confirms a gravid uterus consistent with gestational age. Her capillary blood glucose is 7.8 mmol/L (3.5-7.8).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has received high-flow oxygen, three doses of nebulized salbutamol, and nebulized ipratropium bromide with minimal improvement in her symptoms. When you suggest oral corticosteroids, she expresses concern about the effects on her blood glucose levels and potential harm to her baby.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate counselling regarding oral corticosteroid use?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Corticosteroids are contraindicated during pregnancy due to teratogenic effects","Treatment should be delayed until her blood glucose normalizes","Untreated asthma poses greater risks than corticosteroid use","Alternative non-steroidal medications are equally effective","Corticosteroids should be used at half the standard dose"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with an acute asthma exacerbation during pregnancy, complicated by gestational diabetes. She has not responded adequately to initial therapy including high-flow oxygen, nebulized bronchodilators, and ipratropium bromide, indicating the need for escalation of treatment with oral corticosteroids.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUntreated asthma poses greater risks than corticosteroid use\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate counselling. The patient should be informed that poorly controlled asthma can lead to maternal hypoxemia, which poses significant risks to both mother and fetus, including preterm birth, low birth weight, and increased perinatal mortality. These risks far outweigh the manageable risks of temporary hyperglycemia from corticosteroid use. The patient should be reassured that while corticosteroids may temporarily affect her blood glucose levels, this can be managed with increased monitoring and adjustments to her diabetes management plan.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECorticosteroids are contraindicated during pregnancy due to teratogenic effects\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect and potentially harmful advice. Systemic corticosteroids have been used safely during pregnancy for decades and are not considered teratogenic. The benefits of treating acute asthma exacerbations with corticosteroids during pregnancy far outweigh any theoretical risks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETreatment should be delayed until her blood glucose normalizes\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate advice that could lead to dangerous delays in necessary treatment. The priority is treating the acute asthma exacerbation, as continued respiratory distress and hypoxemia pose immediate risks to both mother and fetus. Blood glucose management should occur concurrently with, not before, appropriate asthma treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlternative non-steroidal medications are equally effective\u003C/strong\u003E is misleading information. There are no non-steroidal alternatives that match the efficacy of corticosteroids for treating acute asthma exacerbations. Other medications like magnesium sulfate or ipratropium bromide may be used as adjuncts but are not substitutes for corticosteroids in this clinical scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECorticosteroids should be used at half the standard dose\u003C/strong\u003E is not evidence-based advice. Reducing the dose of corticosteroids may compromise the effectiveness of treatment without significantly reducing the impact on blood glucose levels. Standard dosing should be used to ensure optimal treatment of the asthma exacerbation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe correct approach is to counsel the patient that oral corticosteroids are necessary for her asthma exacerbation and that untreated asthma poses greater risks to her and her baby than the manageable side effects of corticosteroids. She should be informed that her blood glucose will be monitored more frequently during corticosteroid treatment, and adjustments to her diabetes management (diet, metformin, or temporary insulin) will be made as needed. This approach addresses both her respiratory emergency and her concerns about glycemic control and fetal safety.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Untreated asthma during pregnancy poses greater risks to mother and fetus than the manageable side effects of corticosteroids.","Initial management of acute asthma in pregnancy includes high-flow oxygen, nebulized bronchodilators, and ipratropium bromide before oral corticosteroids.","Blood glucose monitoring should be increased when corticosteroids are administered to pregnant women with gestational diabetes."],"references":["Nelson-Piercy C. Handbook of obstetric medicine. 6th ed. Boca Raton: CRC Press; 2021."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83561"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21383"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83561","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/83561"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-